{"title_page": "Mathos", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=May 2012}}\n\n'''Mathos''' ({{lang-xpu|\ud802\udd0c\u202c\ud802\udd08\u202c\ud802\udd00\u202c}}, {{sc|m\u1e6d\u02be}};{{sfnp|Huss|1985|p=[https://books.google.co.kr/books?id=NvEK7kc3qnQC&pg=PA570 570]}} {{lang-grc-gre|\u039c\u03ac\u03b8\u03c9\u03c2}}, ''M\u00e1th\u014ds''; died {{c.|237}}{{nbsp}}BC) was a [[Berber people|Berber]]. He served with distinction as an officer and military leader in the army of [[Carthage]] during the [[First Punic War]] in [[Sicily]] (241-238/7 BC), but his fame rests on his part in the [[Mercenary War]].\n\nThe Carthaginian army was largely [[mercenary]]. At the conclusion of the [[First Punic War]], when because of the terms of the settlement with Rome the Carthaginian government was unable to pay the agreed dues of its mercenaries, Mathos and Spendius, an escaped Roman slave, led their revolt against it. [[Hamilcar Barca]] suppressed the revolt with the help of the Berber leader [[Naravas]] and [[crucifixion|crucified]] Mathos around 237 BC.\n\nMathos is featured as a main character in [[Gustave Flaubert|Gustave Flaubert's]] 1862 historical novel [[Salammb\u00f4]].\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n===Bibliography===\n* {{citation |last=Hoyos |first=Dexter |year=2007 |title=Truceless War: Carthage's Fight for Survival, 241 to 237 BC |publisher=Brill |isbn=9789004160767 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ln7kyVlArk0C&dq=mathos+libyan&source=gbs_navlinks_s |pages=66\u2013100 }}\n* {{citation |last=Huss |first=Werner |title=Geschichte der Karthager |url=https://books.google.co.kr/books?id=NvEK7kc3qnQC&printsec=frontcover |publisher=C.H. Beck |location=Munich |date=1985 }}. {{in lang|de}} \n* Carthage, Libyan Revolt Circa 241-238 BC. BI Shekel (7.79 gm, 12h). Carthage mint. Head of Herakles left wearing lion skin / Lion walking right; Punic \"M\" above. Carradice & La Niece 1 (same rev. die); MAA 53; '''SNG Copenhagen 241'''\n__NOTOC__\n\n==External links==\n* [http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/brill-s-new-pauly/mathos-e726510 Brill\u2019s New Pauly : Classical Studies]\n\n{{-}}\n[[Category:3rd-century BC Berber people]]\n[[Category:Ancient mercenaries]]\n[[Category:Military of Carthage]]\n[[Category:People executed by crucifixion]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=May 2012}}\n\n'''Mathos''' ({{lang-xpu|\ud802\udd0c\u202c\ud802\udd08\u202c\ud802\udd00\u202c}}, {{sc|m\u1e6d\u02be}};{{sfnp|Huss|1985|p=[https://books.google.co.kr/books?id=NvEK7kc3qnQC&pg=PA570 570]}} {{lang-grc-gre|\u039c\u03ac\u03b8\u03c9\u03c2}}, ''M\u00e1th\u014ds''; died {{c.|237}}{{nbsp}}BC) was a [[Berber people|Berber]]. He served with distinction as an officer and military leader in the army of [[Carthage]] during the [[First Punic War]] in [[Sicily]] (241-238/7 BC), but his fame rests on his part in the [[Mercenary War]].\n\nThe Carthaginian army was largely [[mercenary]]. At the conclusion of the [[First Punic War]], when because of the terms of the settlement with Rome the Carthaginian government was unable to pay the agreed dues of its mercenaries, Mathos and Spendius, an escaped Roman slave, led their revolt against it. [[Hamilcar Barca]] suppressed the revolt with the help of the Berber leader [[Naravas]] and [[crucifixion|crucified]] Mathos around 237 BC.\n\nMathos is featured as a main character in [[Gustave Flaubert|Gustave Flaubert's]] 1862 historical novel [[Salammb\u00f4]].\n\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n===Bibliography===\n* {{citation |last=Hoyos |first=Dexter |year=2007 |title=Truceless War: Carthage's Fight for Survival, 241 to 237 BC |publisher=Brill |isbn=9789004160767 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ln7kyVlArk0C&dq=mathos+libyan&source=gbs_navlinks_s |pages=66\u2013100 }}\n* {{citation |last=Huss |first=Werner |title=Geschichte der Karthager |url=https://books.google.co.kr/books?id=NvEK7kc3qnQC&printsec=frontcover |publisher=C.H. Beck |location=Munich |date=1985 }}. {{in lang|de}} 